posts.name: Sam Bowling
posts.cooked:
This year, our team (1810) built a telescoping arm with a double-axis wrist on the top. We’ve had a lot of issues programming one of the axis on the wrist, the one we called roll.

The main issues we’ve had are with it not correctly moving to setpoints, and with oscillations. There’s going to be a hard stop installed on it soon, which we had on earlier in the season but we took it off because one time (not during tuning, during drive practice) the NEO 550 that runs it pushed it full power into the hard stop, which ended up burning the NEO.

How could we go about correcting these issues?

Github Match Video (shows issues)

posts.name: Chadfrom7226
posts.cooked:
Is your code up to date? I don’t see any “wrist” subsystem

I do see and arm with the PIDs set to 0

Sounds possibly like an encoder issue, but It’s hard to tell when it’s not in person. Here’s some things I’d do:

Use advantagekit to log the inputs and outputs. Yes it is a little long to set up but it’s worth it when you have an issue like you’re having now

Make sure your encoder is working right. If it’s a magnetic encoder and loses contact with the magnet, it will output bad data

Use your encoder to reference the motor, then use the motor’s internal encoder for feedback. This allows you to run PIDs on the motor controller, which is faster/higher update rate, and will prevent bad sensor data from affecting your wrist

Use the WPILib units. I see in your arm subsystem you’re converting rotations to degrees. If you use the units library, then it can do that for you automatically. And it allows the programmer to understand exactly what every unit is

posts.name: Natalie Daleo
posts.cooked:
not a coding issue per say, but I would really recommend your team find a way to mount a NEO 1.1 to control your arm instead of a 550. It will last longer due to its higher torque and doesn’t smoke when stall.

From my experience, limit the supply current on the 550 to under at least 70 amps

posts.name: SLAB-Mr.Thomas
posts.cooked: Make sure the encoder magnetic cannot move WRT its shaft. My team had so much backlash in the shoulder that no amount of programming that we know how to do will fix it so we are getting a new shoulder. It looks like kP is too large but I’m sure you tuned it the best you could. You could try a profiled PID controller either WPILib or in the motor controller.
